abstractText>&lt;p>The project examines the relationship between organisational behaviour and broader institutional forces. Its focus is on how organisational dynamics such as culture, identity, and control are influenced by external social processes. &lt;br />&lt;br />The research is based on an ethnographic study conducted in a social enterprise in the East of England. Social enterprise represents an especially interesting context in which to examine these issues. Specifically, social enterprises have been placed under increasing pressure from funders and policy makers to become more commercially focused and to develop more of their revenue through market-based activity. At the same time, they have been placed under increasing pressure from funders and policy makers to improve their social impact and to adopt particular practices in order to make them more accountable to stakeholders. &lt;br />&lt;br />The need to be both more commercially orientated and to achieve greater social outcomes has generated a series of organisational tensions that many social enterprises have struggled to reconcile. At the heart of these tensions are issues of culture, identity and control. In addition to contributing to organisation theory, the research is intended to yield important insights for social enterprises seeking to manage the apparent conflict between the creation of social and commercial value.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2013-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>197225</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Invited talk at Kingston University</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or pres