Symposium abstract: Throughout the last century, public corporations have been the emblematic organizational form of the contemporary capitalism. However, at the turn of the new century, their dominance as the typical form of business organization has gradually declined (Davis, 2011), and this trend is accompanied by the growth of alternative organizational forms such as mutuals, cooperatives, state-owned enterprises, social enterprises and public-private hybrid organizations, possibly representing a historical transition towards the organizationally diverse capitalism (Schneiberg, 2011). This symposium traces this emerging trend by drawing on diverse academic investigations into novel organizational forms which would serve as alternatives to 20th-century corporations. In doing so, we seek to attract scholarly attention to this emerging phenomenon, and to encourage future organizational research to go beyond the rigid frame of corporations and embrace the novel research possibility enabled by the enhanced organizational diversity in future economy.



I gave a talk entitled &amp;quot;Challenges and Opportunities for Social Enterprise in Contemporary Capitalism: A View from the Inside&amp;quot; in which I used data from my ESRC funded study to consider social enterprise as an alternative to the corporation.

