Follow up discussions with PhD students.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-6510233270.4795832b177c42</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>I have described the impact of my research on Keystone Development Trust - the social enterprise in which I conducted my ethnography - in another section.

Here I would like to emphasise a much broader impact that was not envisioned when I began the study.

Following my Fellowship, I began working with Neil Stott, the Chief Executive of Keystone, on social enterprise related teaching and events at the Judge Business School. The was very successful and led directly to the creation of the Centre for Social Innovation at Cambridge, which is based at the Judge:

http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/faculty-research/centres/social-innovation/

I am the Academic Director of the Centre and Neil is the Executive Director. It has already organised a series of events and initiatives supporting social enterprise, including a recent conference on poverty. Perhaps most importantly it allowed the Judge to become a partner in Social Incubator East, a social enterprise accelerator in Cambridge. Neil and I are also leading the development of a new part-time Masters degree in Social Innovation, which is designed to augment participants capacity to engage in leadership for social change. This is a very exciting development and will ensure the impact of the ESRC award lasts far into the future. Our first cohort of students will start in October 2016.</gtr:description><gtr:id>5EA25DA8-4F69-44AE-A8A4-385C557D9DA8</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>54608163607642.53133426</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Much research in organization studies assumes that organizations exist in a kind of a vacuum and often ignores the role of broader social and institutional processes in shaping organizational behaviour. On the other hand, research on the social and institutional context of organizations tends to ignore what happens inside organizations. This research seeks to help bridge these two perspectives and to address what is sometimes called the 'micro-macro divide' in the study of organizations. To investigate these issues I spent nine months working (unpaid) at Keystone, a social enterprise in the East of England. Keystone runs a series of business ventures and a range of social and community initiatives. 

The study has led to three papers (one of which is still in development). The first paper explores what happens when organizations become aligned with 'unpopular' or stigmatized groups in their institutional environments. It shows that organization can themselves become stigmatized through a process of 'stigma contagion'. This process has profound effects not only on their identity and legitimacy. The second paper explores what happens when organizations attempt to heal conflicts or rifts in their institutional environment. It shows how organizations can use particular kinds of institutional work in order to break down barriers between rival groups. The third paper, currently being drafted, explores how individuals in organizations experience, and use to their advantage, multiple pressures in the environment.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>My findings are particularly important for researchers interested in the potential and limitations of organizations that support migrants. For academics, additional work on how tensions within communities can be eased by social purpose organizations represents an important avenue for future research. This links to broader theoretical issues in social sciences about the extent to which actors can exercise agency when addressing deep rooted social problems.

My project also has implications with respect to research methods. Specifically, it shows that participant observation can result both in data with the potential for publication in major journals, and have a significant impact on the organizations in which researchers are based. This type of 'engaged scholarship' may provide a template for others going forward.

For practitioners, an important aspect of my findings concerns how organizations that support migrants can manage their reputations and avoid stigmatization. And where stigmatization does occur, it suggests possible strategies for managing the likely negative consequences internally. More broadly, my findings suggest that managing organizational identity represents a critical issue for leaders of hybrid organizations.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>97D6DF1E-80F1-4EC8-876E-AF96210EA159</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>54607ecd6298d9.47573317</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>7BC92596-A343-4F5F-9EDF-A0B656B7F4B5</gtr:id><gtr:title>Social innovation: a window on alternative ways of organizing and innovating</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Innovation</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/c4c1efe2aacfd67e915d3708c0166e40"><gtr:id>c4c1efe2aacfd67e915d3708c0166e40</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Tracey P</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2016-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>58ab5d1dcb5f30.33025757</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>54728901-4325-4ADA-958C-4FF83953896F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Managing the Consequences of Organizational Stigmatization: Identity Work in a Social Enterprise</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Academy of Management Journal</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/c4c1efe2aacfd67e915d3708c0166e40"><gtr:id>c4c1efe2aacfd67e915d3708c0166e40</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Tracey P</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</g